&gt;   &gt; I always listen to EVP&#39;s with high quality headphones. In the &quot;tomorrow let you know&quot; EVP, I do hear something....just can&#39;t be sure that it is a voice. I does have a cadence similar to someone speaking, but it could just as easily be something present in the environment-a natural background noise. There is no way for me to tell for certain as it is just too feint. I can&#39;t make out any clear words. Sure-I could probably matrix some in, but that is all it would be. For an EVP to be considered proof positive of spirit communication by the community at large, it has to be clear enough that many people hear the same thing, without hints or coaxing. If you have to have high quality devices to make it out, it just isn&#39;t good enough. That does not mean it isn&#39;t a true EVP, just that it isn&#39;t good enough to stand as evidence. As for the whistle, it sounded like feedback to me as well, but I will have to take you word for it that you were no where near any other electronics or EMF&#39;s that could contribute to feedback. Even so, if I am trying to remain unbiased and objective, there is no way for me to say this is a spirit, without personally being with you when you caught it. The only thing I can still say about it is could be, but for me it is non conclusive. If someone does not hear what you are hearing, try to remain objective and just understand that it isn&#39;t personal. You have to understand that with just these recordings alone, there is no way to scientifically prove what you have recorded is spirit communication. If you could get consistent, intelligent question and answer recordings, then you would be alot closer. Here again, we are back to the &quot;So what?&quot; thing. You don&#39;t HAVE to prove anything scientifically, unless you want others to completely believe in your evidence. The theory that is being kicked around is that some EVP&#39;s are personal, and only meant for the person recording them to hear. If this is the case, no matter how clear something is to you, others may not hear it. April ----- Original Message ----- From: James W. Hyslope To: EVP-ITC@...m Sent: Friday, May 15, 2009 12:02 PMSubject: [EVP-ITC] Re: what you hear is what you get
&gt;   &gt; Okay, I can respect that. If you can&#39;t hear them then it must be either mechanical (sound card or headphones)or maybe your hearing has loss in those frequencies....Some of these are not very clear or loud enough too. But many will depend on your computer sound card & your headphones. I have let an older man listen (in his late 60&#39;s) and he has heard most all of the audio. Same with a few guys at work. Some hear them right away, and others can&#39;t until I loop the actually EVP for a few tries. I personally use a Dell Latitude D430 to hear these. I can hear some on my cell phone. Headphones are a must....or you won&#39;t hear anything either way. *But some can be heard on cell phone without headphones. The conversion to MP3 has also caused some loss, but I am still able to hear them when I review from this site (but I have the repetive hearing syndrome in this area no doubt). Although I do have some disbelief (shock) that a few of these are not discernable. Go back and listen to &quot;tomorrow let you know&quot; is in a gruffy-robotic melodic tone at the very end but with higher natural volume. And if you couldn&#39;t hear the whistle...I would suggest the need to remove the cotton from the ear :) As for feedback.....feedback from what? I only had one recorder working here. I would rather hear someone say &quot;I&quot; made the whistle....that would be more understandable. And is very true....if someone &quot;tells&quot; the group that THIS is supposed to be what WAS said, then is very difficult to clear the mind to hear it any other way. Kinda like trying to hum another song while a different one is playing :) --- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, &quot;April Abercrombie&quot; &lt;april@&gt; wrote:
